justification:
Copsil Gold Press Mat was designed by Mel Douglas in 1994 and manufactured by Marathon Belting Ltd. in 2005. This woven brass and copper fabric, used as a press mat for industrial lamination processes, employs a silicon-elastomer in the weft to prevent deformation of the weave under compression. Textile structure is of the utmost importance to the ultimate performance of the fabric as the herringbone twill weave produces a flat surface with high brass content, maximizing thermal efficiency, while the reversal of the herringbone balances the spring of the elastomer to prevent mat shifting during the lamination process. 
&amp;nbsp;
The Cooper-Hewitt collection contains historic and contemporary examples of this type of textile structure, but this particular example employs a pure industrial application. The Copsil Gold Press Mat demonstrates the strength of these fibers and textile structure while showing the unintended intrinsic beauty of industrial textiles.
